DeepMetal: An Intelligent Metal Recommendation System¶

TDI Capstone Proposal¶

Alexander Sack¶

pisymbol@gmail.com¶

November 2018¶

Why DeepMetal?¶

  • Combine my passion for music with my one for data science
    • I'm a founder of the website Metal-Fi and a guest writer for the blog Angry Metal-Guy, one the most popular metal sites on the web with over a million views per month.
  • Leverage state-of-the-art deep learning and NLP frameworks to build a robust sentiment analysis classifier
  • Questions that need answers:
    • Which subgenre of metal garners the most favorable reviews?
    • Given my favorite metal band is X, what new album should I be listening to?
    • Do bands with more released albums get better or worse overtime?
    • Can we predict the rating of a new review based on prior reviews?

"Angry Metal-AI": A TDI Case Study¶

  • Angry Metal Guy is a reviewed based blog where new metal records are scored by its writing staff on a five point scale in half point increments.
  • Built multiple sentiment analysis classifiers using Naive Bayes (sklearn) and RNNs(keras/Tensorflow, GloVE/word2vec embeddings)
  • Demonstrated my ability to apply modern data science techniques on a real world dataset.

ratings = []
for i in df.index:
    rating = np.nan
    mobj = rating_regex.search(df.loc[i, 'review'])

# Multi reviews are terribly indexed (read: not indexed) on AMG. A multi review is a review
# that contains two or more embedded reviews/ratings for a particular release.
#
# What we do here is for each multi review, we take the arithmetic mean of the embedded reviews
# as the final rating score. This obviously has the by product of mincing words between authors but
# that's OK since our model is meant to be author agnostic.
ratings = []
for i in df.index:
    words = df.loc[i, 'review'].split()
    matches = re.findall(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[i, 'review'])
    if len(matches) > 1:
        ratings = []
        for match in matches:
            mobj = re.search(r'\s*(\d(\.\d+)?)(\/(\d+(\.\d)?))?', match[1])
            if mobj:
                ratings.append(mobj.group(1))
        if len(ratings) > 1:
            mean = np.mean(list(map(float, ratings)))
            print(i, df.loc[i, 'title'], ratings, mean)
            df.loc[i, 'rating'] = mean

# Technically speaking, AMG's ratings are matched to certain words:
#
# Rating System
# 5.0 - Perfect
# 4.5 - Excellent
# 4.0 - Great
# 3.5 - Very Good
# 3.0 - Good
# 2.5 - Mixed
# 2.0 - Disappointing
# 1.5 - Bad
# 1.0 - Embarrassing
# 0.5 - Pathetic
# 0.0 - Worthless
#
# Let's do another pass but this time convert the rating word)(s) to a score
word2rating = {
                'Perfect' : 5.0,
                'Excellent': 4.5,
                'Great': 4.0,
                'Very Good': 3.5,
                'Good': 3.0,
                'Mixed': 2.5,
                'Disappointing': 2.0,
                'Bad': 1.5,
                'Embarrassing': 1.0,
                'Pathetic': 0.5,
                'Worthless': 0.0
}

for unrated in unrated_indexes:
    mobj = re.search(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[unrated, 'review'])
    if mobj:
        # Remember that we are filtering UTF-8 encoded strings so normalize
        # before casefolding below.
        wordRating = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', mobj.group(2)).strip()
        wordRating = wordRating.strip('!')
        if unrated == 1982:
            r1982 = wordRating
        foundRating = False
        for key, value in word2rating.items():
            if key.casefold() == wordRating.casefold():
                df.loc[unrated, 'rating'] = value
                foundRating = True
                break
        if not foundRating:
            print(unrated, wordRating)

# Now extract the words from the reviews, remove stop words and stem.
def review2words(review, stem=True):
    regex = re.compile('[^a-zA-Z]')
    text = regex.sub(' ', review)
    words = text.lower().strip().split()
    words = [word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    if stem:
        words = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in words]

    return " ".join(words)
df['words'] = df['review'].apply(review2words)
df['words_cnt'] = df['words'].apply(lambda x: len(x.split(' ')))

In [30]:
def prepare_amg_data(data):
    """Prepare training and test sets from AMG reviews."""
    
    data_train = data['train']['pos']+data['train']['neg']
    data_test = data['test']['pos']+data['test']['neg']
    labels_train = [1]*len(data['train']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['train']['neg'])
    labels_test = [1]*len(data['test']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['test']['neg'])
    data_train, labels_train = shuffle(data_train, labels_train)
    data_test, labels_test = shuffle(data_test, labels_test)
    
    # Return a unified training data, test data, training labels, test labets
    return data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test

data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test = prepare_amg_data(data)
print("AMG reviews (combined): train = {}, test = {}".format(len(data_train), len(data_test)))

AMG reviews (combined): train = 2602, test = 650

--- Raw review ---
Iron Savior is one of those "comfortable old shoe" kind of bands. Every album is essentially the same and the quality ratio is generally respectable. They were never much for shifting stylistic paradigms and it's fair to call them the AC/DC of overblown sci-fi power metal, but as long as the music was good,it was all fine. Sure,their recent outputhasn't exactly rivaled their classic early period stuff, but they never dropped a total dud either and 2011s The Landing was plenty of fun in all it's overproduced, studio-abusingbombast.
Since their band lineage traces back to both Helloween and Gamma Ray, it's no shock they serve upheaping doses of Germanic style Euro-power with all the typical genre conceits. However,Iron Savior always stood slightly apart by incorporating heavier guitars, rougher vocals and a classic metal spirit.That heaviness has led to some winning tunes and kept their material from becoming too fluffy and pirate-shirty. Rise of the Herofeaturesthe beloved Iron Savior sound and style, but unfortunately, the songs themselves are surprisingly flat and poorly executed.Somefeel forced, others are filler and a few are total clunkers. It's alsooverlong and contains a disastrous cover tune midstream which blows up the whole album. Not as heroic as you hoped, eh?
Despite the various shortcomings, thereare a few good cuts in the vein of classic Savior, with opener "Last Hero" being the best of the bunch. It sports a big, over-the-top chorus (as all proper Savior songs should) and satisfying meat and taters riffs. Also enjoyable is "Revenge of the Bride," which is a zippy, old school burner inspired by the Kill Bill movies, and "From Far Beyond Time" which has a classic Savior sound and a bit of Gamma Ray theatrics. "Burning Heart" is more of a traditional metal anthem withballsy riffing and rough vocals, but it's also too cheesy and a bit forced(and it mayhave the worst DIY video of all time, featuring Piet Sielck singing his lines as he drives to work or something).
Less convincing are tracks like "Thunder From the Mountains," "Iron Warrior" and "Dragon King" which all come across as flat and uninspired, despite some cool, British Steel-esqueriffing on the latter. Worse still is the awkward and slightly uncomfortable power-ballad "Demon" which goes nowhere fast, and closer "Fistraiser," whichscreams filler to the heavens. The fatal coup de grace is the cover version of Mando Diao's "Dance With Somebody," which is so awful and ill-conceived, it rivals Celtic Frost's infamous cover of Wall of Voodoo's "Mexican Radio" for sheer head-scratching befuddlement. If it was relegated to a bonus track, it would be a piffleto be ignored at all costs, but dropping it into the meat of the album is a highly dubious stratagem and ultimately, a platter killer.
As always, I love Piet's rough, raspy vocals which are so unlike the usual balls-stuck-in-car-door histrionics so common in power metal. He always reminded me of Perry McCarty of long forgotten Warrior (go find their Fighting for the Earth album, trust me) and his harsher delivery works especially well alongside the heavy, meaty riffs Iron Savior is known for. Most importantly,he always sounds metal and mean, even when things veer into ber cheese (except on "Dance With Somebody," of course). He and Joachim Kustner do a good job delivering big riffs and fun harmonies and whether they're in speedy, Helloween-y mode or their stripped-down, early 80s Judas Priest style, theyconsistently write engaging, enjoyableleads. Sadly, the songs they drop them into aren't all that good or consistent this time out.
I still go back the first few Savior albums often and I'll always be a sucker fortheir blend of old school metal and Euro-power, but Rise of the Hero feels like a rush job that doesn't represent what the band is capable of. The sound is there, the energy is there, but the songs just aren't. Worth a spin for diehard fans, but it's clearly not them at their best. Everyone else, go grab Unification or Dark Assault.

features_train = pr.normalize(features_train)
features_test = pr.normalize(features_test)
clf1 = GaussianNB()
clf1.fit(features_train, labels_train)

print("[{}] Accuracy: train = {}, test = {}".format(
        clf1.__class__.__name__,
        clf1.score(features_train, labels_train),
        clf1.score(features_test, labels_test)))

maxlen = 300
training_samples = 2500
validation_samples = 500
max_words = 1000

tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=max_words)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(texts)
sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(texts)

word_index = tokenizer.word_index
data = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=maxlen)

# We will shuffle indexes randomly and then split into
# training, validation, and test sets respectively.
indices = np.arange(data.shape[0])
np.random.shuffle(indices)
data = data[indices]
labels = labels[indices]
sent_labels = sent_labels[indices]

# Train
x_train = data[:training_samples]
y_train = labels[:training_samples]
y_sent_train = sent_labels[:training_samples]

# Validation
x_val = data[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_val = labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_sent_val = sent_labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]

# Test
x_test = data[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_test = labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_sent_test = sent_labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]

# Let's use a GLoVE embedding since we don't have a lot of data to build our own embedding layer

if not os.path.exists(glove_dir):
    os.mkdir(glove_dir)
glove_file = os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.zip')
url = 'http://nlp.stanford.edu/data/glove.6B.zip'
if not os.path.exists(glove_file):
    print("Downloading {0}...".format(url), end="")
    urllib.request.urlretrieve(url, glove_file)
    print("done")
    print("Extracting...", end="")
    glove_zip = zipfile.ZipFile(glove_file, 'r')
    glove_zip.extractall(glove_dir)
    glove_zip.close()
    print("done")
else:
    print("glove6B already installed...")

embeddings_dim = 300
embeddings_index = {}
embeddings_matrix = np.zeros((max_words, embeddings_dim))
with open(os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.300d.txt'), encoding='utf-8') as f:
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs
In [40]:
# Generic function to graph accuracy and loss of various different models
def graph_model(history):
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Sentiment analysis with GLoVE embeddings
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(max_words, embeddings_dim, input_length=maxlen))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
model.summary()
# Use GLoVE embeddings instead of trying to learn them on the fly
model.layers[0].set_weights([embeddings_matrix])
model.layers[0].trainable = False
model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['acc'])
history = model.fit(x_train, y_sent_train,
                    epochs=10,
                    batch_size=32,
                    validation_data=(x_val, y_sent_val))
model.save_weights('data/pre_trained_sent_glove_model.h5')
model.evaluate(x_test, y_sent_test)
